practical no . 4 configure ip acls to mitigate attacks and ipv6 acls

Aim:
(a) Verify connectivity among devices before firewall configuration.
(b) Use ACLs to ensure remote access to the routers is available only from management station PC-C.
(c) Configure ACLs to mitigate attacks.
(d) Configuring IPv6 ACLs.

Steps:
Step 1: Verify Connectivity

Open Cisco Packet Tracer and create the network topology.

Configure IP address, subnet mask and default gateway on PCs.

Configure IP addresses on router interfaces.

Test connectivity using ping.

Example:

PC> ping 192.168.1.1

Step 2: Configure Standard ACL (Allow only PC-C)

Router> enable
Router# configure terminal
Router(config)# access-list 10 permit 192.168.3.10
Router(config)# access-list 10 deny any
Router(config)# line vty 0 4
Router(config-line)# access-class 10 in
Router(config-line)# exit

Step 3: Configure Extended ACL to Mitigate Attacks

Router(config)# access-list 100 deny tcp any any eq 23
Router(config)# access-list 100 permit ip any any
Router(config)# interface g0/0
Router(config-if)# ip access-group 100 in
Router(config-if)# exit

Step 4: Configure IPv6 ACL

Router(config)# ipv6 unicast-routing
Router(config)# ipv6 access-list BLOCK_IPV6
Router(config-ipv6-acl)# deny tcp any any eq 23
Router(config-ipv6-acl)# permit ipv6 any any
Router(config)# interface g0/0
Router(config-if)# ipv6 traffic-filter BLOCK_IPV6 in

Step 5: Verify

Router# show access-lists
Router# show ipv6 access-list